{TEXT -1 31 "1.  Graphing functions and the " }{TEXT 257 4 "plot" }
{TEXT -1 89 " command.  The Maple command for plotting the graph of an
 explicitly defined function is:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 5 "     " }{TEXT 258 0 "" }{TEXT 259 4 "plot
" }{TEXT 260 0 "" }{TEXT -1 2 "( " }{TEXT 261 4 "expr" }{TEXT -1 2 ", \+
" }{TEXT 266 1 "x" }{TEXT -1 20 "=range [, options]);" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 
"" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 6 "where " }{TEXT 262 4 "e
xpr" }{TEXT 267 1 " " }{TEXT -1 24 "is a symbolic expression" }{TEXT 
264 1 " " }{TEXT -1 48 "which represents the function to be plotted an
d " }{TEXT 263 1 "x" }{TEXT -1 38 " is the independent variable used i
n  " }{TEXT 265 4 "expr" }{TEXT -1 25 "  to define the function." }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 81 "Several o
ptions exist to change way the plot will appear.  These options includ
e:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 126 "  \+
          y=range                       this allows the user to specif
iy the range of output values which Maple will display" }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 113 "            thickness=value           this controls
 the thickness of the plotted curve.  value = 1, 2, 3, 4, or 5" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 119 "            color=value                 \+
this sets the color of the plotted curve.  value = red, green, blue, c
yan, etc." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
160 "For each of the following functions provide a plot to represent t
he graph the function.  Choose a range that will optimally represent t
he features of the graph." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 16 "a.    y = 3x - 1" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" 
